snippet.textDisplay:
I was the same for most of school. When I entered secondary school (starts at 12 years old ends around 18) I loved reading. I was so happy we were being tested on the books as well. Then I got the first test result. From then it got worse with all the Shakespeare and poetry reading analysing metaphors that might be what the author meant at best. Then a few months into my first year of college I was in the college library and saw a book we were made read in secondary. I had 2 free hours and had nothing better to do, so I read 'Of Mice and Men' . I hated this book and its movie because of needing to write about them but with nothing to do while/after reading it... I don't think there's been many books I enjoyed more. I'm on track to reading 70 books this year (about 1.5 a week) and I now hate schools even more for taking that love of reading from me.

TL;DR School made me hate reading. I now plan on reading over a book a week this year.

snippet.textDisplay: I can see what lead Jaiden to dislike reading and I agree it sucks when others tell you what to read. But I was kinda the opposite, throughout primary school I hated reading cause they made us read constantly but then I found goosebumps which I loved. This lead me onto reading teen books and now I absolutely love to read!! It’s just so amazing to imagine things described in words! I love reading so much that I’m taking literature instead of regular English. So Jaiden I suggest that you give reading another chance, I promise you don’t have to analyse any books or find the themes and underlying meanings. Just read and let your imagination run wild. (Also “To Kill a Mockingbird” is a fantastic book)
